WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.230 --> 00:00:03.410
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab.

00:00:03.410 --> 00:00:06.620
This is a free, complete course for the CCNA.

00:00:06.620 --> 00:00:10.330
If you like these videos, please subscribe
to follow along with the series.

00:00:10.330 --> 00:00:14.869
Also, please like and leave a comment, and
share the video to help spread this free series

00:00:14.869 --> 00:00:15.869
of videos.

00:00:15.869 --> 00:00:17.610
Thanks for your help.

00:00:17.610 --> 00:00:21.390
In this video we will look at software-defined
networking.

00:00:21.390 --> 00:00:25.599
In the first video of this network automation
series we already covered the fundamentals

00:00:25.599 --> 00:00:30.509
such as centralizing the control plane in
an SDN controller, northbound and southbound

00:00:30.509 --> 00:00:32.070
APIs, etc.

00:00:32.070 --> 00:00:39.580
So, in this video we’ll take a more in-depth
look at one of Cisco’s SDN offerings, SD-Access,

00:00:39.580 --> 00:00:40.600
Software-Defined Access.

00:00:40.600 --> 00:00:44.410
We’ll cover exam topics 6.3 and 6.4.

00:00:44.410 --> 00:00:49.440
You’ll learn new terms like overlay, underlay,
and fabric which are essential concepts in

00:00:49.440 --> 00:00:52.500
SDN that we haven’t covered yet.

00:00:52.500 --> 00:00:56.059
Here’s what we’ll cover in this video.

00:00:56.059 --> 00:00:59.570
First I’ll briefly review the points about
SDN that you’ll need to remember for this

00:00:59.570 --> 00:01:01.150
video.

00:01:01.150 --> 00:01:05.760
Then I’ll introduce Cisco’s SD-Access,
including important concepts like underlay,

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:07.610
overlay, and fabric.

00:01:07.610 --> 00:01:12.760
I’ll also introduce Cisco’s DNA Center
management platform, which is an essential

00:01:12.760 --> 00:01:18.520
part of SD-Access, and compare it to traditional
network management.

00:01:18.520 --> 00:01:23.190
Make sure to watch until the end of the video
for a bonus practice question from Boson Software’s

00:01:23.190 --> 00:01:26.890
ExSim, the best practice exams for the CCNA.

00:01:26.890 --> 00:01:31.100
Let’s reviews some points about SDN.

00:01:31.100 --> 00:01:36.130
SDN is an approach to networking that centralizes
the control plane into an application called

00:01:36.130 --> 00:01:38.340
a controller.

00:01:38.340 --> 00:01:42.300
Traditional control planes use a distributed
architecture, which means that every network

00:01:42.300 --> 00:01:44.780
device has its own control plane.

00:01:44.780 --> 00:01:49.030
The control planes of each network device
use protocols like OSPF to communicate with

00:01:49.030 --> 00:01:54.130
each other and share routing information,
each device has its own ACLs and security

00:01:54.130 --> 00:01:55.130
rules, etc.

00:01:55.130 --> 00:01:58.310
That’s a distributed control plane.

00:01:58.310 --> 00:02:03.430
An SDN controller centralizes control plane
functions like calculating routes.

00:02:03.430 --> 00:02:08.160
Network devices no longer use OSPF to share
information with each other, instead they

00:02:08.160 --> 00:02:12.800
share information with the controller, which
takes that information and calculates routes

00:02:12.800 --> 00:02:14.650
for the entire network.

00:02:14.650 --> 00:02:19.939
Now, depending on the SDN solution the entire
control plane might be centralized in the

00:02:19.939 --> 00:02:24.800
SDN controller, or perhaps only part of the
control plane is centralized, leaving some

00:02:24.800 --> 00:02:29.130
functions on the individual network devices.

00:02:29.130 --> 00:02:34.580
The controller can interact programmatically
with the network devices using APIs.

00:02:34.580 --> 00:02:39.049
Specifically it uses what we call the southbound
interface to do that.

00:02:39.049 --> 00:02:43.120
Then there is also the northbound interface,
which is what allows us to interact with the

00:02:43.120 --> 00:02:45.840
controller using our scripts and applications.

00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:52.560
Okay, those are the fundamental points of
SDN that I wanted to review.

00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:57.129
And here’s one more look at the SDN architecture
we covered in the first video of this automation

00:02:57.129 --> 00:02:58.519
section.

00:02:58.519 --> 00:03:02.730
The applications are on top, the controller
in the middle, and the network devices on

00:03:02.730 --> 00:03:03.840
the bottom.

00:03:03.840 --> 00:03:07.859
Actually, these three ‘layers’ of the
architecture have names.

00:03:07.859 --> 00:03:10.099
On top there is the application layer.

00:03:10.099 --> 00:03:14.439
This layer contains scripts and applications
that tell the SDN controller what network

00:03:14.439 --> 00:03:16.780
behaviors are desired.

00:03:16.780 --> 00:03:21.219
Note that this isn’t the application layer
of the OSI model, this is a totally different

00:03:21.219 --> 00:03:22.219
concept.

00:03:22.219 --> 00:03:24.269
We’re not talking about the OSI model here.

00:03:24.269 --> 00:03:27.099
Anyway, next is the control layer.

00:03:27.099 --> 00:03:31.439
This contains the SDN controller that receives
and processes instructions from the application

00:03:31.439 --> 00:03:32.980
layer.

00:03:32.980 --> 00:03:37.150
Although this is a separate concept from the
‘control plane’, this layer is also what

00:03:37.150 --> 00:03:41.090
contains the centralized control plane of
the network.

00:03:41.090 --> 00:03:44.909
And finally there is the infrastructure layer,
which contains the actual devices that are

00:03:44.909 --> 00:03:48.029
responsible for forwarding messages across
the network.

00:03:48.029 --> 00:03:53.709
I didn’t mention these layers in earlier
videos, so take the time to learn them now.

00:03:53.709 --> 00:03:58.951
The application layer contains apps and scripts
for instructing the SDN controller, the control

00:03:58.951 --> 00:04:03.230
layer contains the SDN controller, and the
infrastructure layer contains the network

00:04:03.230 --> 00:04:04.340
devices.

00:04:04.340 --> 00:04:09.989
Okay, so I’ve told you the basics of what
SDN is and its purpose, but we still haven’t

00:04:09.989 --> 00:04:12.379
looked at a specific example of SDN.

00:04:12.379 --> 00:04:19.110
So, let’s take a look at one, Cisco Software-Defined
Access.

00:04:19.110 --> 00:04:23.720
Cisco SD-Access is Cisco’s SDN solution
for automating campus LANs.

00:04:23.720 --> 00:04:28.170
So, office wired and wireless LANs, for example.

00:04:28.170 --> 00:04:33.820
Cisco has other SDN solutions, for example
ACI, Application Centric Infrastructure, is

00:04:33.820 --> 00:04:37.700
their SDN solution for automating data center
networks.

00:04:37.700 --> 00:04:41.740
Remember when I explained spine-leaf architecture
earlier in the course?

00:04:41.740 --> 00:04:46.010
That is used extensively in ACI data center
networks.

00:04:46.010 --> 00:04:50.530
Cisco also has SD-WAN, their SDN solution
for automating WANs.

00:04:50.530 --> 00:04:54.280
But for now let’s look at SD-Access.

00:04:54.280 --> 00:05:01.750
Cisco DNA, Digital Network Architecture, Center
is the controller at the center of SD-Access.

00:05:01.750 --> 00:05:07.310
In the previous video about REST APIs we sent
a REST API call to DNA Center, so perhaps

00:05:07.310 --> 00:05:08.600
you remember that name.

00:05:08.600 --> 00:05:12.720
Okay, let’s look at the basic SD-Access
architecture.

00:05:12.720 --> 00:05:16.500
At the center, in the control layer, we have
DNA Center.

00:05:16.500 --> 00:05:21.700
And then under it we have the network devices
in our campus LAN in the infrastructure layer.

00:05:21.700 --> 00:05:27.930
These devices form the fabric of SD-Access,
and I’ll explain that term in the next slide.

00:05:27.930 --> 00:05:33.380
In the application layer we have our scripts
and apps that interact with DNA center.

00:05:33.380 --> 00:05:38.830
These could be tools we develop, third-party
tools, or tools directly from Cisco.

00:05:38.830 --> 00:05:43.680
DNA Center itself also has a GUI that we can
use to control it.

00:05:43.680 --> 00:05:48.440
Okay, so that’s the basic architecture of
Cisco’s SD Access.

00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:53.081
Notice how it fits perfectly into the SDN
Application layer, Control layer, Infrastructure

00:05:53.081 --> 00:05:54.970
layer model.

00:05:54.970 --> 00:05:57.300
Next let’s look at that term ‘fabric’.

00:05:57.300 --> 00:06:01.930
To understand the fabric, you need to understand
two other terms.

00:06:01.930 --> 00:06:07.240
First, the underlay is the underlying physical
network of devices and connections, wired

00:06:07.240 --> 00:06:14.400
and wireless, which provide IP connectivity,
for example with a routing protocol like IS-IS.

00:06:14.400 --> 00:06:18.680
Usually I’d use OSPF as an example, since
it’s the most common interior gateway routing

00:06:18.680 --> 00:06:24.630
protocol, but soon you’ll see why I chose
IS-IS for this example.

00:06:24.630 --> 00:06:29.210
Basically the underlay is a bunch of multilayer
switches and their connections.

00:06:29.210 --> 00:06:34.770
Then the overlay is the virtual network built
on top of the physical underlay network.

00:06:34.770 --> 00:06:41.990
For example, SD-Access uses a protocol called
VXLAN, virtual extensible LAN, to build tunnels.

00:06:41.990 --> 00:06:47.150
And fabric is the term we use to refer to
the combination of the overlay and underlay,

00:06:47.150 --> 00:06:50.660
the physical and virtual network as a whole.

00:06:50.660 --> 00:06:53.580
For example, this is the underlay network.

00:06:53.580 --> 00:06:57.640
The physical multilayer switches and their
connections form the underlay, and they are

00:06:57.640 --> 00:07:04.900
perhaps running IS-IS to share routing information
and provide connectivity throughout the network.

00:07:04.900 --> 00:07:11.250
Then the overlay network consists of VXLAN
tunnels, for example between these two switches.

00:07:11.250 --> 00:07:15.340
When hosts in the LAN communicate with each
other, their traffic is sent over the VXLAN

00:07:15.340 --> 00:07:16.340
tunnels.

00:07:16.340 --> 00:07:19.000
That’s the overlay network.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:24.880
And the fabric refers to the physical and
virtual network as a whole, overlay plus underlay.

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:27.670
Both are necessary to make SD-Access work.

00:07:27.670 --> 00:07:32.450
Okay, now let me give a little more detail
about both the underlay and overlay.

00:07:32.450 --> 00:07:36.210
So, let’s talk about the underlay.

00:07:36.210 --> 00:07:40.660
The underlay’s purpose is to support the
VXLAN tunnels of the overlay.

00:07:40.660 --> 00:07:44.930
To make a virtual network of tunnels, the
devices first need to be connected and able

00:07:44.930 --> 00:07:49.750
to reach other of course, so the underlay
is very important.

00:07:49.750 --> 00:07:53.230
There are three different roles for switches
in SD-Access.

00:07:53.230 --> 00:07:58.080
Those are edge node, these are switches that
connect to end hosts, like a traditional access

00:07:58.080 --> 00:07:59.960
layer switch.

00:07:59.960 --> 00:08:05.220
Then there are border nodes, which connect
to devices outside of the SD-Access domain,

00:08:05.220 --> 00:08:08.450
for example connecting to a WAN router.

00:08:08.450 --> 00:08:14.400
And finally there are control nodes, which
use a protocol called LISP, Locator ID Separation

00:08:14.400 --> 00:08:17.230
Protocol, to perform various control plane
functions.

00:08:17.230 --> 00:08:22.390
I think LISP is far beyond what you need to
know for the CCNA, so just know that it is

00:08:22.390 --> 00:08:26.110
used for the control plane of SD-Access.

00:08:26.110 --> 00:08:30.800
Note that you can add SD-Access on top of
an existing network if your network hardware

00:08:30.800 --> 00:08:33.030
and software supports it.

00:08:33.030 --> 00:08:39.089
This is called a brownfield deployment, when
you add it on to an already existing network.

00:08:39.089 --> 00:08:44.620
If you’re curious which hardware supports
it, you can google ‘Cisco SD-Access compatibility

00:08:44.620 --> 00:08:49.950
matrix’, but you don’t have to know the
specific devices for the CCNA.

00:08:49.950 --> 00:08:54.370
And also note that in this case DNA center
won’t configure the underlay, because this

00:08:54.370 --> 00:08:59.009
could be a major risk to the current working
production network.

00:08:59.009 --> 00:09:03.850
Ideally you will be using a greenfield deployment,
which is a totally new network built for the

00:09:03.850 --> 00:09:06.529
purpose of SD-Access.

00:09:06.529 --> 00:09:12.300
In this case DNA center will configure the
devices for the optimal SD-access underlay.

00:09:12.300 --> 00:09:16.999
For example, all switches are layer 3 and
use IS-IS as their routing protocol.

00:09:16.999 --> 00:09:20.910
That’s why I mentioned IS-IS in the example
earlier.

00:09:20.910 --> 00:09:26.649
Additionally all links between switches are
routed ports, so STP is not needed to avoid

00:09:26.649 --> 00:09:28.500
Layer 2 loops.

00:09:28.500 --> 00:09:33.930
And edge nodes, so access switches, act as
the default gateway of end hosts.

00:09:33.930 --> 00:09:38.829
This is known as a routed access layer, we’ve
brought layer 3 all the way down to the access

00:09:38.829 --> 00:09:41.410
switches that end hosts connect to.

00:09:41.410 --> 00:09:44.069
Let me demonstrate with a diagram.

00:09:44.069 --> 00:09:46.899
Here’s a traditional LAN.

00:09:46.899 --> 00:09:53.730
Notice that STP is used to avoid layer 2 loops,
and an FHRP, for example HSRP, is used by

00:09:53.730 --> 00:09:58.660
the distribution layer switches to provide
a redundant default gateway for the end hosts.

00:09:58.660 --> 00:10:03.870
So, to send traffic out of their local network,
they will send it to the virtual IP provided

00:10:03.870 --> 00:10:09.020
by the FHRP, 192.168.1.1.

00:10:09.020 --> 00:10:14.700
In an SD-access underlay, however, all connections
between switches are Layer 3 and IS-IS is

00:10:14.700 --> 00:10:17.790
used to exchange routing information.

00:10:17.790 --> 00:10:22.650
Note that STP is no longer needed, and an
FHRP isn’t needed either.

00:10:22.650 --> 00:10:27.680
Instead, the access layer switches are the
default gateways of the end hosts.

00:10:27.680 --> 00:10:31.680
Now we have a routed access layer.

00:10:31.680 --> 00:10:36.230
Now let me briefly introduce a few aspects
of the SD-Access overlay.

00:10:36.230 --> 00:10:39.850
First, LISP provides the control plane of
SD-Access.

00:10:39.850 --> 00:10:44.180
A list of mappings of EIDs to RLOCs is kept.

00:10:44.180 --> 00:10:46.220
Let me explain those terms.

00:10:46.220 --> 00:10:53.509
EIDs, endpoint identifiers, identify end hosts
connected to edge switches, and RLOCs, routing

00:10:53.509 --> 00:10:58.490
locators, identify the edge switch which can
be used to reach the end host.

00:10:58.490 --> 00:11:02.430
Of course, there is a lot more detail to cover
about LISP, but I think with just that you

00:11:02.430 --> 00:11:05.899
can see how it differs from the traditional
control plane.

00:11:05.899 --> 00:11:10.820
Instead of a traditional routing table to
locate destination hosts, a DNS-like system

00:11:10.820 --> 00:11:13.509
of mappings is used.

00:11:13.509 --> 00:11:20.020
Cisco TrustSec, CTS, provides policy control
such as QoS and security policy.

00:11:20.020 --> 00:11:25.740
Just remember that name, Cisco TrustSec, you
don’t have to know about its functionality.

00:11:25.740 --> 00:11:30.529
And finally VXLAN provides the data plane
of SD-Access, the tunnels that are used to

00:11:30.529 --> 00:11:33.189
actually forward traffic in the data plane.

00:11:33.189 --> 00:11:37.500
Let’s look at how VXLAN tunnels work with
LISP.

00:11:37.500 --> 00:11:43.100
Notice that SW3 is a control node, so it is
important for the function of LISP.

00:11:43.100 --> 00:11:49.670
PC2 is connected to SW2, and it tells the
control node that PC2 is reachable via SW2.

00:11:49.670 --> 00:11:53.189
So, SW3 creates that mapping.

00:11:53.189 --> 00:11:58.660
Now PC1 wants to send traffic to PC2, so it
sends it to the default gateway, SW1.

00:11:58.660 --> 00:12:02.610
SW1 asks SW3, how can I reach PC2?

00:12:02.610 --> 00:12:06.249
And SW3 informs it that PC2 is reachable via
SW2.

00:12:06.249 --> 00:12:12.379
So, the message from PC1 is forwarded over
a VXLAN tunnel between SW1 and SW2.

00:12:12.379 --> 00:12:15.980
Okay, that’s all I’ll say about the overlay
for now.

00:12:15.980 --> 00:12:20.559
VXLAN does more than just create tunnels,
it provides a lot of features to SD-Access

00:12:20.559 --> 00:12:23.160
which I won’t get into in this video.

00:12:23.160 --> 00:12:28.670
Just know the difference between fabric, overlay,
and underlay, and know some basics of SD-Access

00:12:28.670 --> 00:12:36.420
like edge node, border node, and control node,
LISP, VXLAN, and Cisco TrustSec.

00:12:36.420 --> 00:12:39.309
Now let’s look a bit more at DNA Center.

00:12:39.309 --> 00:12:42.339
DNA Center itself has two main roles.

00:12:42.339 --> 00:12:48.220
First, it is the SDN controller used in SD-Access,
as I mentioned earlier.

00:12:48.220 --> 00:12:53.060
Additionally it can be a network manager in
a traditional network that isn’t using SD-Access.

00:12:53.060 --> 00:12:58.689
In that case, although it doesn’t provide
SD-Access functions, it still acts as a central

00:12:58.689 --> 00:13:02.620
point to monitor, analyze, and configure the
network.

00:13:02.620 --> 00:13:07.499
Although I will mention both purposes, for
this lecture we’re focusing on the SD-Access

00:13:07.499 --> 00:13:08.949
application.

00:13:08.949 --> 00:13:14.600
Note that DNA Center is a software application
installed on Cisco UCS server hardware.

00:13:14.600 --> 00:13:19.160
I mentioned Cisco UCS in the virtualization
lecture of this course.

00:13:19.160 --> 00:13:25.550
DNA Center has a REST API, as you already
know, which can be used to interact with it.

00:13:25.550 --> 00:13:31.389
And its southbound interface supports protocols
such as NETCONF and RESTCONF, as well as traditional

00:13:31.389 --> 00:13:37.519
protocols Telnet, SSH, and SNMP to control
and monitor devices.

00:13:37.519 --> 00:13:44.310
DNA Center enables something called intent-based
networking, IBN, yet another buzzword.

00:13:44.310 --> 00:13:49.429
Basically, the goal is to allow the engineer
to communicate their intent for network behavior

00:13:49.429 --> 00:13:54.779
to DNA Center, and then DNA Center will take
care of the details of the actual configurations

00:13:54.779 --> 00:13:57.639
and policies on the devices.

00:13:57.639 --> 00:14:01.550
It simplifies the process, and allows engineers
to spend time on more important things than

00:14:01.550 --> 00:14:05.370
analyzing and configuring policies on devices
one at a time.

00:14:05.370 --> 00:14:07.980
Here’s one example.

00:14:07.980 --> 00:14:11.990
Traditional security policies using ACLs can
become very cumbersome.

00:14:11.990 --> 00:14:16.819
For example, ACLs can have thousands of entries,
and the intent of entries is easily forgotten

00:14:16.819 --> 00:14:21.179
with time and as engineers leave and new engineers
take over.

00:14:21.179 --> 00:14:25.259
Looking at another engineer’s configurations
and trying to figure out the intent is often

00:14:25.259 --> 00:14:27.429
not an easy task.

00:14:27.429 --> 00:14:31.389
And configuring and applying ACLs correctly
across a network is cumbersome and leaves

00:14:31.389 --> 00:14:32.730
room for error.

00:14:32.730 --> 00:14:38.440
DNA Center, on the other hand, allows the
engineer to specify the intent of the policy,

00:14:38.440 --> 00:14:43.040
for example this group of users can’t communicate
with this group, or this group can access

00:14:43.040 --> 00:14:48.100
this server but not that server, etc, and
DNA Center will take care of the exact details

00:14:48.100 --> 00:14:51.490
of implementing the policy.

00:14:51.490 --> 00:14:55.279
This is what configuring policies on DNA Center
looks like.

00:14:55.279 --> 00:14:57.959
Notice on the left here we have source groups.

00:14:57.959 --> 00:15:02.699
Of course, you’d have to define the groups
first, which users belong in which groups.

00:15:02.699 --> 00:15:05.490
And here we have those same groups as destination.

00:15:05.490 --> 00:15:09.860
Up here we have the legend for the colors
in the policy grid.

00:15:09.860 --> 00:15:12.559
Note that the entire grid is white now, so
default.

00:15:12.559 --> 00:15:17.990
However, let’s say any traffic sourced from
users in the developers group and destined

00:15:17.990 --> 00:15:20.810
for the Test_Servers group should be permitted.

00:15:20.810 --> 00:15:23.819
Now, what about traffic sourced from the guest
group?

00:15:23.819 --> 00:15:28.350
They shouldn’t be able to access our servers,
so we’ll make that red.

00:15:28.350 --> 00:15:30.899
How about users in the employees group?

00:15:30.899 --> 00:15:35.471
Maybe that depends on various factors, we
can’t just permit or deny all traffic, so

00:15:35.471 --> 00:15:39.220
we would want to make a custom policy for
that.

00:15:39.220 --> 00:15:43.149
We can go ahead and define policies like this,
it’s a very simple and straightforward way

00:15:43.149 --> 00:15:48.009
of creating and applying policies across the
entire SD-Access fabric.

00:15:48.009 --> 00:15:51.139
No need to configure policies on devices one
at a time.

00:15:51.139 --> 00:15:55.379
I’m not showing the whole process here of
course, but one thing to note is that the

00:15:55.379 --> 00:15:59.860
engineer can write an explanation for each
policy made, making it much easier to understand

00:15:59.860 --> 00:16:01.730
the purpose of policies later.

00:16:01.730 --> 00:16:07.149
Okay, now let’s take a look at some of the
other features of DNA Center.

00:16:07.149 --> 00:16:11.730
In the menu on the left side you can see there
are various sections, and I’ve opened the

00:16:11.730 --> 00:16:13.639
design section.

00:16:13.639 --> 00:16:19.379
Here we can build the network hierarchy, manage
IP addresses and subnets, configure DHCP servers,

00:16:19.379 --> 00:16:22.610
DNS servers, etc, among other things.

00:16:22.610 --> 00:16:28.079
Here, for example, I’m looking at one site,
SJC-20, on a map.

00:16:28.079 --> 00:16:31.660
You can map your enterprise’s sites all
over the world and create hierarchies based

00:16:31.660 --> 00:16:35.040
on country, etc.

00:16:35.040 --> 00:16:39.420
In the policy menu you can configure policies
like the example I showed you earlier.

00:16:39.420 --> 00:16:43.670
You tell DNA Center how the network devices
should behave, and DNA Center will change

00:16:43.670 --> 00:16:47.639
that into configurations on the devices in
the network.

00:16:47.639 --> 00:16:50.569
For example, here’s that group-based access
control page again.

00:16:50.569 --> 00:16:54.920
A simple and logical way to configure network
policies.

00:16:54.920 --> 00:16:59.850
In the provision menu we can manage our device
inventory and add new devices.

00:16:59.850 --> 00:17:03.220
Other services are available as well, as you
can see in the menu.

00:17:03.220 --> 00:17:06.060
Here’s the inventory page.

00:17:06.060 --> 00:17:10.760
In the side bar you can see that there are
3 unassigned devices under global.

00:17:10.760 --> 00:17:15.199
By default, when you add devices to DNA Center
they will be under the global site, until

00:17:15.199 --> 00:17:18.120
you assign them to a specific site.

00:17:18.120 --> 00:17:22.110
You can see their status of ‘managed’
here, this means they are under control of

00:17:22.110 --> 00:17:25.079
DNA Center, they are not independent devices.

00:17:25.079 --> 00:17:29.860
This is also the default setting when you
register a device in DNA Center.

00:17:29.860 --> 00:17:32.910
Here you can see the compliance status of
the devices.

00:17:32.910 --> 00:17:37.370
The top device is compliant with our policies,
but the bottom two aren’t.

00:17:37.370 --> 00:17:43.919
I clicked on one of the non-compliant devices,
and you can see why it is labeled as non-compliant.

00:17:43.919 --> 00:17:48.049
The software image, the version of IOS, is
not up to date.

00:17:48.049 --> 00:17:54.000
The version should be 17.03.03, but currently
it is 16.11.1c.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:57.730
We can use DNA Center to update that later
if we want.

00:17:57.730 --> 00:18:03.100
And here you can see that it is also non-compliant
with some security advisories.

00:18:03.100 --> 00:18:07.440
Anyway moving on, in the assurance section
of the menu you can monitor the status of

00:18:07.440 --> 00:18:08.600
the network.

00:18:08.600 --> 00:18:12.690
You can make sure the devices are all up and
running without issues.

00:18:12.690 --> 00:18:16.640
For example, here I can see which devices
in the network are considered ‘healthy’

00:18:16.640 --> 00:18:18.049
by DNA Center.

00:18:18.049 --> 00:18:22.559
3 of 4 devices are in good health, and 1 of
them simply has no health data.

00:18:22.559 --> 00:18:26.930
Okay, that’s all we’ll look at for now,
but if you want to look around DNA Center

00:18:26.930 --> 00:18:33.120
yourself you can check out the DevNet sandbox
at sandboxdnac.cisco.com, and you can see

00:18:33.120 --> 00:18:35.380
the username and password here.

00:18:35.380 --> 00:18:40.670
I highly recommend checking it out and looking
around at what DNA Center has to offer.

00:18:40.670 --> 00:18:46.340
Okay, that was a quick look at DNA Center,
but to be honest you don’t have to be familiar

00:18:46.340 --> 00:18:49.860
with all of the functions of DNA Center for
the CCNA.

00:18:49.860 --> 00:18:54.771
Basically, just understand its role as a network
controller in SD-Access architecture, and

00:18:54.771 --> 00:18:59.550
also understand that it can be a network management
platform in a traditional network.

00:18:59.550 --> 00:19:04.809
However, the exam topics do state that you
should be able to compare DNA Center-enabled

00:19:04.809 --> 00:19:07.559
device management with traditional device
management.

00:19:07.559 --> 00:19:13.040
Actually, I’ve covered most of these points
already when I first introduced network automation,

00:19:13.040 --> 00:19:14.590
but let’s review to make sure.

00:19:14.590 --> 00:19:19.809
First, let’s review some characteristics
of traditional network management.

00:19:19.809 --> 00:19:23.980
Devices are configured one-by-one via SSH
or console connection.

00:19:23.980 --> 00:19:27.670
This is what we’ve been doing throughout
the labs in this course.

00:19:27.670 --> 00:19:31.289
Devices are manually configured via console
connection before being deployed.

00:19:31.289 --> 00:19:33.960
This means when deploying a new device to
a network.

00:19:33.960 --> 00:19:39.070
You first have to manually set it up before
connecting it to the network.

00:19:39.070 --> 00:19:42.580
Configurations and policies are managed per-device,
in a distributed manner.

00:19:42.580 --> 00:19:45.299
There is no central management.

00:19:45.299 --> 00:19:49.610
New network deployments take a long time due
to the manual labor required.

00:19:49.610 --> 00:19:54.110
Setting up dozens of new devices manually
takes a lot of time, and also errors and failures

00:19:54.110 --> 00:19:57.309
are more likely due to increased manual effort.

00:19:57.309 --> 00:20:01.919
Now, I don’t want to make it seem like traditional
network management is bad, but you should

00:20:01.919 --> 00:20:05.080
be aware of these potential downsides.

00:20:05.080 --> 00:20:09.770
Now some characteristics of DNA Center-based
network management.

00:20:09.770 --> 00:20:14.370
Devices are centrally managed and monitored
from the DNA Center GUI or other applications

00:20:14.370 --> 00:20:16.760
using its REST API.

00:20:16.760 --> 00:20:21.880
In this video I showed you the DNA Center
GUI, but using the REST API other applications

00:20:21.880 --> 00:20:25.889
can be used to interact with DNA Center too.

00:20:25.889 --> 00:20:31.350
With DNA Center, the administrator communicates
their intended network behavior to DNA Center,

00:20:31.350 --> 00:20:37.040
which changes those intentions into configurations
on the managed network devices.

00:20:37.040 --> 00:20:40.000
Configurations and policies are centrally
managed, they’re all stored and managed

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:42.260
on DNA Center.

00:20:42.260 --> 00:20:44.320
Software versions are also centrally managed.

00:20:44.320 --> 00:20:49.140
DNA Center can monitor cloud servers for new
versions and then update the managed devices

00:20:49.140 --> 00:20:50.830
when needed.

00:20:50.830 --> 00:20:55.590
In this video you saw an example of DNA Center
showing us an alert for a device with an old

00:20:55.590 --> 00:20:57.380
software version.

00:20:57.380 --> 00:21:01.929
Finally, with DNA Center new network deployments
are much quicker.

00:21:01.929 --> 00:21:07.420
New devices can automatically receive their
configurations from DNA Center without manual

00:21:07.420 --> 00:21:08.420
configuration.

00:21:08.420 --> 00:21:12.740
Not only is this faster, human error is reduced
too, which is a huge bonus.

00:21:12.740 --> 00:21:16.000
Okay, that’s all I’ll say about this.

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:19.419
Most of these points we have already covered,
but make sure you’re aware of them because

00:21:19.419 --> 00:21:21.580
it is mentioned on the exam topics.

00:21:21.580 --> 00:21:24.370
Okay, let’s review what we covered.

00:21:24.370 --> 00:21:29.720
We first reviewed SDN, and I newly introduced
the terms application layer, control layer,

00:21:29.720 --> 00:21:31.200
and infrastructure layer.

00:21:31.200 --> 00:21:37.049
Then, as an example of SDN, I introduced some
concepts of Cisco SD-Access.

00:21:37.049 --> 00:21:41.570
The main takeaways from this section are the
concepts of underlay, overlay, and fabric.

00:21:41.570 --> 00:21:44.440
Make sure you understand those concepts.

00:21:44.440 --> 00:21:48.860
Then I showed you some functions of Cisco
DNA Center, and compared network management

00:21:48.860 --> 00:21:52.000
with DNA Center to traditional network management.

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:57.410
Remember, DNA Center is an SDN controller
in SD-Access architecture, but it can also

00:21:57.410 --> 00:22:03.179
be used as a general network management tool
even in networks that don’t use SD-Access.

00:22:03.179 --> 00:22:07.950
Make sure to watch until the end of the quiz
for a bonus practice question from Boson Software’s

00:22:07.950 --> 00:22:10.980
ExSim, the best practice exams for the CCNA.

00:22:10.980 --> 00:22:14.460
Okay, let’s go to quiz question 1.

00:22:14.460 --> 00:22:20.190
Which of the following terms describes the
network of devices and physical connections?

00:22:20.190 --> 00:22:24.539
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:22:24.539 --> 00:22:29.340
Okay, the answer is A, underlay.

00:22:29.340 --> 00:22:33.950
The underlay refers to the underlying physical
network, and then the virtual overlay network

00:22:33.950 --> 00:22:35.700
is built on top of it.

00:22:35.700 --> 00:22:38.740
The combination of underlay and overlay is
called the fabric.

00:22:38.740 --> 00:22:42.980
Okay, let’s go to question 2.

00:22:42.980 --> 00:22:46.590
In which of the following layers would you
expect to find scripts that interact with

00:22:46.590 --> 00:22:47.929
the controller?

00:22:47.929 --> 00:22:52.539
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:22:52.539 --> 00:22:57.549
Okay, the answer is B, application.

00:22:57.549 --> 00:23:01.940
In SDN architecture, the application layer
includes apps and scripts that can be used

00:23:01.940 --> 00:23:05.620
to interact with the controller, which is
in the control layer.

00:23:05.620 --> 00:23:09.720
Finally the bottom layer is the infrastructure
layer, which includes the network devices.

00:23:09.720 --> 00:23:14.190
Okay, let’s go to question 3.

00:23:14.190 --> 00:23:18.539
Which of the following is a characteristic
of an optimal SD-Access underlay network as

00:23:18.539 --> 00:23:20.630
configured by DNA-Center?

00:23:20.630 --> 00:23:25.120
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:23:25.120 --> 00:23:31.470
Okay, the answer is B, all links between switches
are layer 3.

00:23:31.470 --> 00:23:35.390
This means that spanning tree is not needed,
and no links will have to be disabled because

00:23:35.390 --> 00:23:37.519
there is no risk of layer 2 loops.

00:23:37.519 --> 00:23:41.500
Okay, let’s go to question 4.

00:23:41.500 --> 00:23:46.029
Which protocol is used to create virtual tunnels
in the SD-Access overlay?

00:23:46.029 --> 00:23:50.640
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:23:50.640 --> 00:23:55.669
Okay, the answer is D, VXLAN.

00:23:55.669 --> 00:23:59.250
It is used to create virtual tunnels in the
overlay network.

00:23:59.250 --> 00:24:03.480
And although we didn’t cover any details
at all, the ‘extensible’ in the name ‘virtual

00:24:03.480 --> 00:24:06.140
extensible LAN’ is very important.

00:24:06.140 --> 00:24:10.049
It means that VXLAN supports many different
features which are used by SD-Access.

00:24:10.049 --> 00:24:15.010
Okay, let’s go to question 5.

00:24:15.010 --> 00:24:18.539
Which of the following are valid switch roles
in Cisco SD-Access?

00:24:18.539 --> 00:24:24.770
(select three) Pause the video now to select
the best answers.

00:24:24.770 --> 00:24:32.360
Okay, the answers areA, C, and D. Control,
border, and edge nodes.

00:24:32.360 --> 00:24:36.460
These are the three different switch roles
in Cisco SD-Access, and there is no such thing

00:24:36.460 --> 00:24:37.940
as a management node.

00:24:37.940 --> 00:24:40.540
Okay, that’s all for the quiz.

00:24:40.540 --> 00:24:45.840
Now let’s take a look at a bonus question 
in Boson Software’s ExSim for CCNA.

